args: So our ingredients for dinner are the plants\nwe foraged from the woods, as well as the\ntrout you so impressively caught.
I also have some Hinomotoan rice that\nI brought with me from the castle,\nas well as a few spices.
We went to the trouble of buying this pot,\nso how about we cook the rice with all of\nthe other ingredients?
Cooking a variety of ingredients with rice\nis a Hinomotoan staple, is it not?
Sure is! It lets the flavors meld perfectly.
I'd actually been hoping to learn some\nHinomotoan cooking for myself.
Then let's get the prep going!
Add the rice... Add the ingredients...\nAdd the spice... We're ready, Mitsuba.
Now we just have to put it on the flame.
I hope it comes out delicious.
Me too. I'll keep an eye on the heat.
Thank you. I've heard it's quite difficult to\nproperly cook Hinomotoan rice, after all.
Luckily, that sort of thing is my forte.\nYou can just take five here, Cleo.
Okay, we should be ready.\nLet's open 'er up.
I can scarce contain my excitement!
The outside is completely burned,\nbut the center is sort of...gooey?

Well, that is unfortunate. Wind direction
and weather are hard to gauge in the
mountains, so I imagine they affected
the heat of the flame.
And after I went on about how good I am\nat managing the heat, too...
You've done nothing wrong, Mitsuba.\nIn fact, I was careless myself.
But I wasted all of our ingredients...\nAND your precious time!
I made you climb a MOUNTAIN for\nheck's sake, and now all you get is\na gooey burnt mess for dinner.
Can't believe I thought I'd find the\nsecret to being a better chef out here...
I don't think today was a waste at all.
True, climbing the mountain was not my\nfavorite part, but the rest of the time we\nspent together was delightful.
We may have failed with the food,\nbut we still managed to make some\ntruly wonderful memories together.
I do—and I ALSO think failure makes for\na stronger memory than a success.
Making a fine memory of your failure\nis what outdoor cooking is all about!
You know, I've never thought about it\nthat way before.
That's because you always made food for\nyour customers, not just for yourself.
Yeah, Dad was pretty unforgiving with\nmistakes—he yelled at me a lot.
But that's not what scared me\naway from slipping up.

Once I took over the restaurant, I knew
any mistake I made would bring shame to
the business. The more I thought about
that, the less I tolerated my own failures.
...Heh. The smell of this burned rice\nis actually taking me back.

One time after I burnt a batch, Dad gave
me this long lecture about how hard the
farmers who grew the rice had worked...
so we ended up eating it together anyway.
Heh, so even something as modest as\nburnt rice brings back fond memories of\nyour father. How sweet.

And as such, shall we eat this together?
This rice was born of a failure that came
after we overcame many hardships—which
makes it quite meaningful, if you ask me.
Here you are, Mitsuba! One heaping\nhelping of rice with extra burned parts!
*chomp* *squish* Ha ha ha ha!\nGosh, the middle of it really is like\ntrying to chew a sponge.
Ha ha ha ha ha! It's terrible, Cleo!\nI mean, it is REALLY bad! Ha ha ha!
Hee hee! *munch* ...Actually, the\nburned rice doesn't taste half bad.
*munch* Hey, you're right. It's NOT bad.\nI mean...relatively. Ha ha ha ha ha!
Okay, this is DEFINITELY the hardest I've\never laughed in my life while eating rice.
Yet another of the pleasures\ngained from outdoor cooking.
Now let us eat until our bellies are round!
Oh, I'm on it. More, please!
